# alm14b_speedup_unsloth.diff
#
# Unsloth FastLanguageModel integration for ALM 14B LoRA training.
# STACKS ON TOP of the base 7 speedup patches (flash_attention, torch_compile,
# fused_adamw, disable_act_ckpt, dataloader, nccl_env, tf32_cudnn).
#
# TARGET:  r7 (NOT r6). r6 is the base-patches round; r7 is Unsloth on top.
# SCOPE:   single-H100 only. Unsloth + FSDP is possible but requires manual
#          Accelerate/DeepSpeed config and is out of this audit's scope.
#          If --unsloth AND --fsdp are both set, the trainer aborts.
# APPLY:   cd anima && git apply --check shared/patches/alm14b_speedup_unsloth.diff
#          (do NOT apply yet — audit only; r6 is in flight)
#
# ── Unsloth facts (cited from upstream, 2026-04-15) ───────────────────────
#
# 1. Qwen2.5-14B-Instruct IS supported.
#    Source: https://huggingface.co/unsloth/Qwen2.5-14B-Instruct
#    Quote: "2x-2.4x faster finetuning" and "50-74% less memory usage" for
#    Unsloth LoRA vs HF+peft, per the HF model card.
#
# 2. FastLanguageModel.from_pretrained signature (unsloth/models/loader.py):
#      model_name, max_seq_length, dtype, load_in_4bit=True, load_in_8bit=False,
#      device_map="sequential", trust_remote_code=False,
#      use_gradient_checkpointing="unsloth", *args, **kwargs
#    - load_in_4bit defaults to True — we MUST pass False (no-quantization rule).
#    - use_gradient_checkpointing="unsloth" is Unsloth's own checkpointing,
#      more efficient than HF's reentrant variant. Accepts True/False/"unsloth".
#    - attn_implementation is NOT a named kwarg. Unsloth binds its own
#      flash-attention path internally; passing HF's attn_implementation via
#      **kwargs is a no-op at best and a conflict at worst. So the Unsloth
#      branch MUST drop the HF attn_implementation="flash_attention_2" kwarg.
#
# 3. torch.compile: Unsloth calls unsloth_compile_transformers() internally
#    with fullgraph=True. Stacking user torch.compile(mode="max-autotune") on
#    top would double-compile and break Dynamo traces. Therefore the --unsloth
#    branch MUST skip the r6 torch.compile() call.
#
# 4. Gradient checkpointing: Unsloth's internal "unsloth" variant is
#    incompatible with HF model.gradient_checkpointing_enable() called
#    externally. We therefore do NOT call gradient_checkpointing_enable()
#    on the Unsloth path — Unsloth handles it via from_pretrained kwarg.
#
# 5. FSDP/DDP: Unsloth docs say "Multi-GPU ... supported through libraries
#    like Accelerate and DeepSpeed ... the process can be complex and
#    requires manual setup" and "We're working hard to make multi-GPU support
#    much simpler". For single-H100 this is irrelevant. For multi-GPU r7 the
#    audit recommendation is to stay on the base-7 path (no Unsloth).
#
# ── Expected uplift (cited) ──────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Upper bound: 2.0x-2.4x faster + 50-74% less memory (HF model card, LoRA).
# These numbers are Unsloth-vs-HF-default; our r6 already has FA2 +
# fused AdamW + compile + no act-ckpt, so the delta from r6→r7 is SMALLER
# than the headline 2x. Realistic expectation r6→r7: +15% to +35% throughput
# and 10-20% less peak VRAM (qualitative — not benchmarked). Needs empirical
# measurement on the pod once r6 establishes a baseline.
#
# ── Conflicts with base 7 patches ────────────────────────────────────────
#
# | base patch         | unsloth interaction                          |
# |--------------------|----------------------------------------------|
# | flash_attention    | REPLACED — Unsloth binds its own FA path     |
# | torch_compile      | REPLACED — Unsloth compiles internally       |
# | disable_act_ckpt   | REPLACED — use_gradient_checkpointing arg    |
# | fused_adamw        | KEPT — optimizer is unchanged                |
# | dataloader         | KEPT — data path is unchanged                |
# | nccl_env           | KEPT — launcher env is unchanged (no-op here)|
# | tf32_cudnn         | KEPT — global torch backend toggle           |
#
